Back in the early Athlon 64 days I had a CPU with two completely snapped off pins that wouldn't boot.
So figuring I had nothing to lose I stripped a network cable and cut the (solid) cores to length, shoved them directly in the socket on the motherboard... and sure enough it worked!
A brutish method but damn did it feel good when that sucker booted up!

snippet.textDisplay: You can get the CPU to work even without soldering. In the socket holes which correspond to the broken pins, place thin but rigid metal wires or pins (like from an old VGA cable or a non functional CPU) and make them to just the correct height. Once you install the chip back along with the heatsink, those pins will make contact and allow the CPU to work like new. I did this with a very old Pentium 4 PGA 478 system. That system still works to this day and has been donated to an organization for educational purposes. :)

snippet.textDisplay:
Couple additional tips from someone who does RMAs on small electronics:
Rest your hand on the table for stable handling of the tweezers.
Don't heat pins while holding them; it gives them more thermal mass, thus making the process last longer than it could.
Putting a solder mask on top will likely screw you right over, that would only work in an oven. Or with excessive heat from a hot-air rework station.
Try to wear an ESD wristband when working on 'not dead' electronics.

What i would do is flux the contacts, tin the contacts (or use the old tin thats still there), then heat the contacts with hot air.
When tin goes shiny, add pins while keeping the heat closely on there. About an inch should do it. (what she said) Adding a 'cold' pin makes the tin harden in a brittle fashion; to avoid that, we keep heating while putting the pin in place. If the tin is still shiny, remove the hot air or keep heating until shiny. Then let it cool off.

Any questions feel free :)

snippet.textDisplay:
Great adventure LMG.
Did make me cringe a tad but the end results were worth it. Next time you REALLY need to use the 4mm tip and DON'T use the solder mask as it's for re-soldering the pads with pre-sized solder balls, not that job(I'm sure you helped Louis Rossman re-ball a chip). All the mask is doing is draining the heat from the rework station and stopping the heat from getting to the pads. It would actually have been easier to use a traditional soldering iron as the heat would have traveled through the pin.
Instead, set the FAN speed lower on the SMD rework station and let the "tension" of the solder grab the pin. It's the "tension" than makes the pins suddenly snap into place.
When you've finished flush with Isopropyl alcohol and dry with low heat on the rework station. 👍
